one alla carta archeologica del territorio di Tindari\u003C/i> (Rome: MediaGEO, 2013)\u003C/span>","https://www.zotero.org/groups/isicily/items/X2SEXMRX",{"type":167,"bibl":168},"discussion",[20],{"editor":170,"principal":172,"contributors":173,"change":189},{"_":171,"ref":97},"Jonathan Prag",{"_":171,"ref":97},[174,177,181,185],{"_":171,"xml:id":175,"ref":176},"JP","http://orcid.org/0000-0003-3819-8537",{"_":178,"xml:id":179,"ref":180},"James Cummings","JCu","http://orcid.org/0000-0002-6686-3728",{"_":182,"xml:id":183,"ref":184},"Simona Stoyanova","SS","https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3914-9569",{"_":186,"xml:id":187,"ref":188},"Alex Antoniou","AA","http://orcid.org/0000-0001-7077-0703",{"_":190,"when":191,"who":97},"Jonathan Prag revised from autopsy","2026-03-05",{"n":100,"url":101,"height":102,"width":103,"desc":104,"surfaceType":105},[194],{"atLeast":195,"atMost":195},125,[197,198,199],"L'année épigraphique: revue des publications épigraphiques relatives a l'antiquité romaine., 1888-","Manganaro, 1989, Iscrizioni Latine nuove e vecchie della Sicilia","Fasolo, 2013, Tyndaris e il suo territorio. Volume 1. Introduzione alla carta archeologica del territorio di Tindari",[201,202,203],"R46KDTZX","EZMBJ6GN","X2SEXMRX",[205,206,207,22,28,32,208,209,210,211,209,212,213,126],"isic000680","fragment of a monumental latin inscription",{"_":5},"tyndaris","tindari","sicilia","sicily","antiquarium di tindari","latin",[],{"title":216,"body":217,"divs":218,"editions":243,"images":253,"handnote":259},"ISic000680. Fragment of a monumental latin inscription","\u003Cdiv id=\"editions\">\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Alex Antoniou, Jonathan Prag\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-interpretive\" lang=\"la\">  \u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>Vale[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Alex Antoniou, Jonathan Prag\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-diplomatic\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-diplomatic\">\u003Ca id=\"al1-diplomatic\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>VALE[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"facsimile-images\">\u003Ch2>Facsimile Images\u003C/h2>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000680_tiled.tif\">\u003Cimg title=\"I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana - Dipartimento dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana; photo J. Prag 2022-07-12\" src=\"ISic000680_tiled-thumb.tif\">\u003C/a>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000680.jpg\">\u003Cimg title=\"I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana - Dipartimento dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana; photo J. Prag 2022-07-12\" src=\"ISic000680-thumb.jpg\">\u003C/a>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"apparatus\">\u003Ch4>Apparatus criticus\u003C/h4>\u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan>\u003Cspan>Text from autopsy\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"translation\">\u003Ch2> translation\u003C/h2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">  \u003C/p>\u003Cp>  \u003C/p>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"commentary\">\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>Manganaro proposed to restore the text as a dedication to [Divo Flavio] Vale[rio Constantino], on the model of ILS 652. In doing so, he did not note that the plaque appears to be intact on the left. However, more fundamental is the nature of the text/monument and the form of the letters. A fourth-century imperial honorific in this form would be hard to parallel on the island. The scale of the text strongly implies a building inscription, rather than a simple honorific, and the fact that the left margin is intact, presumably requires that this is one of several slabs on the facade of a building, since this is unlikely to be the beginning of the text. Although theoretically possible to be a later third or fourth century CE text, the letter forms do seem to make this unlikely, and a date in the high empire (first or second century CE) seems more plausible. VALE[--] is most plausibly part of a name, and given that imperial names with this element only begin with Valerian in the 250s CE and then emperors of the fourth century, perhaps we should imagine the name of a provincial governor instead. In any case, the reconstruction and the implied date proposed by Manganaro is difficult to sustain.\u003C/p>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"bibliography\">\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> 1989.0338g \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001283\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001283\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Manganaro 1989 163 no.11 fig.11 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001831\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001831\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Fasolo 2013 77 no.13 fig.42 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002011\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002011\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"handnote\">\u003Cp>Fine, wide, v-cut monumental letters with elegant serifs. The A is closed at the top by the horizontal 'serif'.\u003C/p> Line 1  125  Interlineation line 1 to 2    \u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"license\"> Licensed under a Creative Commons-Attribution 4.0 licence. \u003C/div>",[219,222,225,228,231,234,237,240],{"id":220,"html":221},"editions","\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Alex Antoniou, Jonathan Prag\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-interpretive\" lang=\"la\">  \u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>Vale[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Alex Antoniou, Jonathan Prag\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-diplomatic\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-diplomatic\">\u003Ca id=\"al1-diplomatic\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>VALE[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>",{"id":223,"html":224},"facsimile-images","\u003Ch2>Facsimile Images\u003C/h2>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000680_tiled.tif\">\u003Cimg title=\"I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana - Dipartimento dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana; photo J. Prag 2022-07-12\" src=\"ISic000680_tiled-thumb.tif\">\u003C/a>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000680.jpg\">\u003Cimg title=\"I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana - Dipartimento dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana; photo J. Prag 2022-07-12\" src=\"ISic000680-thumb.jpg\">\u003C/a>",{"id":226,"html":227},"apparatus","\u003Ch4>Apparatus criticus\u003C/h4>\u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan>\u003Cspan>Text from autopsy\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>",{"id":229,"html":230},"translation","\u003Ch2> translation\u003C/h2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">  \u003C/p>\u003Cp>  \u003C/p>",{"id":232,"html":233},"commentary","\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>Manganaro proposed to restore the text as a dedication to [Divo Flavio] Vale[rio Constantino], on the model of ILS 652. In doing so, he did not note that the plaque appears to be intact on the left. However, more fundamental is the nature of the text/monument and the form of the letters. A fourth-century imperial honorific in this form would be hard to parallel on the island. The scale of the text strongly implies a building inscription, rather than a simple honorific, and the fact that the left margin is intact, presumably requires that this is one of several slabs on the facade of a building, since this is unlikely to be the beginning of the text. Although theoretically possible to be a later third or fourth century CE text, the letter forms do seem to make this unlikely, and a date in the high empire (first or second century CE) seems more plausible. VALE[--] is most plausibly part of a name, and given that imperial names with this element only begin with Valerian in the 250s CE and then emperors of the fourth century, perhaps we should imagine the name of a provincial governor instead. In any case, the reconstruction and the implied date proposed by Manganaro is difficult to sustain.\u003C/p>  ",{"id":235,"html":236},"bibliography","\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> 1989.0338g \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001283\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001283\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Manganaro 1989 163 no.11 fig.11 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001831\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001831\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Fasolo 2013 77 no.13 fig.42 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002011\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002011\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  ",{"id":238,"html":239},"handnote","\u003Cp>Fine, wide, v-cut monumental letters with elegant serifs. The A is closed at the top by the horizontal 'serif'.\u003C/p> Line 1  125  Interlineation line 1 to 2    ",{"id":241,"html":242},"license"," Licensed under a Creative Commons-Attribution 4.0 licence. ",[244,246,249,250],{"html":245},"Text encod